{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613891"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:38:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:38:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16330"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16330","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16330"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9021"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67793"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9021"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16330"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53258"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7516"},{"type":"tags","id":"7518"},{"type":"tags","id":"8556"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21461"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21465"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22699"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67793"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe uveal tract is the vascular middle layer of the eye and consists of three continuous structures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most anterior component of the uveal tract?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Choroid","Ciliary body","Iris","Retina","Tenon\u0027s capsule"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eiris\u003C/strong\u003E is the most anterior component of the uveal tract. The uveal tract consists of three continuous structures from anterior to posterior: iris, ciliary body, and choroid. The iris contains smooth muscle that controls pupil size to regulate light entry into the eye.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eciliary body\u003C/strong\u003E is the middle component of the uvea, located between the iris and choroid. The \u003Cstrong\u003Echoroid\u003C/strong\u003E is the posterior component, providing blood supply to the outer retina.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eretina\u003C/strong\u003E is the innermost neural layer of the eye, not part of the uveal tract. \u003Cstrong\u003ETenon\u0027s capsule\u003C/strong\u003E is a fascial layer surrounding the eye, separate from the uveal tract.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The uveal tract consists of three components from anterior to posterior: iris, ciliary body, and choroid.","The iris is the most anterior part of the uvea and controls the amount of light entering the eye by adjusting pupil size."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53258"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16330"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53258"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T08:43:34+10:30"